<subSubSection pageId="57" pageNumber="58" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="57.[151,1437,258,1686]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,467,402,427]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Differential Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Somewhat similar in habitus to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2011" box="[836,993,403,427]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="biundulata">
<emphasis box="[836,856,403,426]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[872,993,403,427]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">biundulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1878" box="[1011,1089,403,426]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Tetana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1011,1089,403,426]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Tetana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group), including the shape of the sides of the pronotum, which are nearly equally sinuate in front of and behind the widest part (
<figureCitation box="[1238,1331,438,462]" captionStart="FIGURE 75" captionStartId="201.[151,250,1753,1776]" captionTargetBox="[234,1356,209,1718]" captionTargetId="figure-26@201.[220,1368,193,1732]" captionTargetPageId="201" captionText="FIGURE 75. Hydraena biundulata, holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and venter." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5283547" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5283547/files/figure.png" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Figs. 75</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1342,1373,438,462]" captionStart="FIGURE 86" captionStartId="209.[151,250,1753,1776]" captionTargetBox="[197,1392,211,1718]" captionTargetId="figure-26@209.[180,1408,193,1732]" captionTargetPageId="209" captionText="FIGURE 86. Hydraena koma, holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and venter." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5283579" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5283579/files/figure.png" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">86</figureCitation>
); distinguished therefrom by the markedly arcuate anterior margin of the pronotum, the very different metaventral plaques, and the different elytral coloration. Additionally, males have very differently shaped tibiae in the two species. The male genitalia of the two species differ greatly (
<figureCitation box="[794,888,546,570]" captionStart="FIGURES 76–77" captionStartId="202.[151,264,1650,1673]" captionTargetBox="[300,1270,221,1616]" captionTargetId="figure-32@202.[278,1309,193,1629]" captionTargetPageId="202" captionText="FIGURES 76–77. Aedeagi of holotypes. 76. H. insandalia. 77. H. biundulata." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5283551" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5283551/files/figure.png" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Figs. 77</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[899,930,546,570]" captionStart="FIGURES 88–89" captionStartId="211.[151,264,1561,1584]" captionTargetBox="[249,1332,217,1516]" captionTargetId="figure-29@211.[226,1360,193,1540]" captionTargetPageId="211" captionText="FIGURES 88–89. Aedeagi of holotypes. 88. H. koma. 89. H. colorata." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5283585" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5283585/files/figure.png" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">88</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="57" pageNumber="58" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="57.[151,1437,258,1686]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,344,582,607]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" reason="1">Description.</emphasis>
Size: 
<typeStatus box="[428,526,582,606]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">holotype</typeStatus>
(length/width, mm): body (length to elytral apices) 1.64/0.63; head 0.29/0.36; pronotum 0.38/0.45, PA 0.38, PB 0.36; elytra 0.96/0.63. Dorsum of head with frons and clypeus piceous; labrum dark brown; pronotum light brown to testaceous in front of and behind piceous fascia, ratios of color bands, as measured in midline, ca. 6/15/5; elytra dark brown to piceous in ca. anterior 2/5 and narrowly along explanate margin, otherwise elytra light brown to testaceous; legs light brown; maxillary palpi testaceous, tip not darker. Dorsum moderately strongly shining.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="57.[151,1437,258,1686]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Frons punctures ca. 1xef, only slightly larger near eyes, sparser medially; interstices shining, medially 2–5xpd. Clypeus effacedly microreticulate laterally, very finely sparsely punctulate and shining medially. Mentum and postmentum conjointly weakly concave. Mentum effacedly microreticulate, very sparsely very finely punctulate, weakly shining. Postmentum microreticulate, dull. Genae very slightly raised, weakly shining, with small median impression, without posterior ridge. Pronotum subcordiform, distinctively narrowed both in front of and behind widest area; ca. median 1/2 of anterior margin rather markedly arcuate to posterior; punctures on disc ca. 1xpd largest frons punctures, interstices shining, ca. 2–5xpd, punctures anteriorly and posteriorly ca. 2xpd those on disc, and denser; PF1 and PF4 absent; PF2 very shallow, obsolete; PF3 deep, wide.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="57.[151,1437,258,1686]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">
Elytra widest at about midlength; summit of posterior declivity at about midlength; lateral explanate margins moderately wide; on basal 1/3 punctures ca. 1xpd largest pronotal punctures, a few punctures subserial, punctures becoming gradually smaller toward posterior. Intervals not raised, shining, on disc ca. 1–2xpd, as are interstices between punctures of a row. Apices partly missing in 
<typeStatus box="[752,853,1194,1218]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">holotype</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="57.[151,1437,258,1686]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">
Ratios of P2 width and plaque shape (P2/w/l/s) ca. 3/1/6/5. P1 laminate; median carina sinuate in profile, slightly raised between coxae. P2 length/width ca. 5/3, sides very slightly diverging toward blunt apex. Plaques carinate lines, gradually raising from anterior to posterior, at sides of median depression, anteriorly slightly convergent. Metaventrite flat or slightly concave between mesocoxae. AIS width at straight posterior margin ca. 1.5x P2. All legs of moderate length. Profemur (male) with minute tubercle on ventral margin near trochanter; protibia straight, medial margin widened from about midlength to subapically, then narrowed to apex, greatest width ca. 1.5x width at midlength. Mesotibia straight, slender, with many short spine-like setae. Metatibia with medial margin distinctly widened at about midlength, greatest width ca. 1.5x width at apex; lateral margin emarginate. Abdominal apex symmetrical; last tergite (male) with large, deep apicomedian notch. Aedeagus as illustrated (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 88–89" captionStartId="211.[151,264,1561,1584]" captionTargetBox="[249,1332,217,1516]" captionTargetId="figure-29@211.[226,1360,193,1540]" captionTargetPageId="211" captionText="FIGURES 88–89. Aedeagi of holotypes. 88. H. koma. 89. H. colorata." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5283585" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5283585/files/figure.png" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Fig. 88</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
